solution:
This simplifies nicely because $5!$ divides both $6!$ and $7!$ evenly:


\begin{align*}
\frac{6! + 7!}{5!} &=\frac{6!}{5!} + \frac{7!}{5!}\\&= 6 + 6 \cdot 7\\
&= 6 \cdot 8 \\
&= \boxed{48}
\end{align*}

We factor and rearrange the terms in the factorials:

\begin{align*}
\frac{3\cdot 5! + 15\cdot 4!}{6!} &= \frac{3\cdot 5! + 3\cdot 5!}{6!} \\
&= \frac{2\cdot 3 \cdot 5!}{6!} \\
&= \frac{6!}{6!} \\
&= \boxed{1}
\end{align*}

We can simplify directly

\begin{align*}
2\left(\frac{7!}{3!4!}\right) &= 2\left(\frac{7\cdot 6 \cdot 5}{3 \cdot 2 \cdot 1}\right) \\
&= \frac{7 \cdot 6 \cdot 5}{3 \cdot 1} \\
&= 7 \cdot 2 \cdot 5 \\
&= \boxed{70}
\end{align*}

We do some simplification, taking advantage of the fact that $n! = n\cdot (n-1)!$: \begin{align*}
\frac{9!\cdot 5!\cdot 2!}{8!\cdot 6!} &= \frac{9\cdot 8! \cdot 5! \cdot 2}{8!\cdot 6\cdot 5!}\\
&= \frac{9\cdot 2}{6}\\
&= \boxed{3}.
\end{align*}

We can separate the fraction to get $\frac{6!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5!}$. We can then simplify the quotient of factorials:

\begin{align*}
\frac{6!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5!} &= \frac{6\cdot5!}{5!} +\frac{4!}{5\cdot4!}\\
&=6+\frac15\\
&=\boxed{6\frac15}.
\end{align*}

